        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Feb. 2<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi></dateline>
                <salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>

                <p>many thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> kind Letter &amp;c give yrself no
                    trouble about the <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0051">Ph.
                        Tr.</title></bibl>
                    <rs ref="ar0048">plate</rs> for that shall be my care. copies of the <rs ref="ar0047">plates</rs> in <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0050">Sib.
                            Phalain</title></bibl> is all I want: the Book I find I can borrow in
                        <placeName ref="pl0699">London</placeName>. where I shall be in less than a
                    month. parcels may be sent to <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Whiteâ€™s Bookseller</persName>
                    <placeName ref="pl1012">Fleetstreet</placeName>. Letters inclosed to <persName ref="pe0015">Sir R. Mostyn M.P.</persName>
                    <placeName ref="pl0734">Bruton Street</placeName>.</p>
                <p>you make me very happy by the account you transcribed from <persName ref="pe0116">Jo. Frazer</persName>. was he Dean of the isles, or son to him. pray what
                    date. the Indexes will be most welcome.<note type="editorial">See Pennant, <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0008"><hi rend="italic">Tour in Scotland
                                    and Voyage to the Hebrides 1772</hi></title> (Chester: 1774),
                                <biblScope unit="page">p.285</biblScope></bibl>: 'Mr. <hi rend="italic">Frazier</hi>, son to the DEAN of the isles, informed Mr.
                            <hi rend="italic">Sacheverel</hi> governor of the isle of <hi rend="italic">Man</hi>, who visited <hi rend="italic">Iona</hi> in 1688,
                        that his father had collected there three hundred inscriptions, and
                        presented them to the Earl of <hi rend="italic">Argyle</hi>; which were
                        afterwards lost in the troubles of the family.'</note></p>
                <p>If I write little at a time attribute it to the too great affairs I have on hand:
                    but believe me</p>
                <closer><salute>with much esteem y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">T P.</persName></signed></closer>
            </div>
        </body>
